    The stack trace and code reveal that the program is experiencing a stack    
    overflow, which manifests as an EXC_BAD_ACCESS error.                       
                                                                                
    Root Cause Analysis                                                         
                                                                                
     1 Missing Base Case: The function fib(int n) in program.cpp is a           
       recursive implementation of the Fibonacci sequence that lacks a          
       termination condition (base case). It blindly calls fib(n-1) and         
       fib(n-2).                                                                
     2 Infinite Recursion: Because there is no base case, the function will     
       continue to call itself indefinitely. As n decreases, it enters          
       negative numbers (as seen in the stack trace n = -261266).               
     3 Stack Exhaustion: Every recursive call adds a new entry to the call      
       stack. Because the recursion never stops, it eventually consumes the     
       entire memory allocated for the thread's stack, leading to the           
       EXC_BAD_ACCESS (a segmentation fault/stack overflow).                    
                                                                                
    The stack trace shows values like n = -261266, confirming that the          
    function is recursively subtracting from n without ever hitting a limit.    
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Minimal Fix                                                                 
                                                                                
    Add a base case to the fib function to stop the recursion when n reaches 0  
    or 1.                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
       if (n <= 1) {                                                            
         return n;                                                              
       }                                                                        
       return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);                                          
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Thorough Root-Cause Fix                                                     
                                                                                
    While the fix above solves the stack overflow, the naive recursive          
    Fibonacci implementation has exponential time complexity ($O(2^n)$). For    
    an input like n = 100, it would still take an extremely long time to        
    compute even if the base case is added. A production-ready fix should use   
    memoization or an iterative approach to achieve linear time complexity      
    ($O(n)$):                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
         if (n <= 1) return n;                                                  
                                                                                
         std::vector<long long> dp(n + 1);                                      
         dp[0] = 0;                                                             
         dp[1] = 1;                                                             
                                                                                
         for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {                                         
             dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + dp[i - 2];                                     
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         return dp[n];                                                          
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
